ğŸ¦´ BeagleBone Green (BBG)

ğŸ”§ System / Maintenance â€“ Useful Commands & What They Do

- sudo â†’ runs a command with administrator (root) privileges. 
  Needed for changing system files, installing software, or accessing GPIO hardware.
- sudo apt update â†’ refreshes the package list (knows whatâ€™s available to install).
- sudo apt upgrade â†’ installs the latest updates for already-installed software.
- sudo reboot â†’ restarts the BeagleBone safely.
- sudo shutdown now â†’ powers off the BeagleBone.
- ls /dev/gpiochip* â†’ shows available GPIO controllers.
- gpioinfo â†’ prints all GPIO pins, their numbers, and status.

ğŸ“¥ Installing / Downloading

- -wget URL â†’ downloads a file from the internet.
- curl -O URL â†’ alternative way to download files.
- scp file user@beaglebone:/path â†’ copies a file from your computer to the BeagleBone via SSH.
- git clone URL â†’ downloads a full project/repo from GitHub.

ğŸ”Œ GPIO / Hardware

- config-pin P9_15 gpio â†’ configures a pin mode (GPIO, PWM, etc.).
- gpiod (Python library) â†’ lets you control GPIO pins in Python3.
- line.request(..., DIR_OUT) â†’ configures a GPIO pin as output.
- line.set_value(1) â†’ sets pin HIGH (3.3V or 5V, depending).
- line.set_value(0) â†’ sets pin LOW (0V).

ğŸ“€ Reset / Recovery

- Power button hold (10s) â†’ force shutdown.
- Hold BOOT button + power on â†’ boot from microSD card (used for reflashing OS).
- eMMC flash image (from beagleboard.org) â†’ restores BeagleBone to factory OS.

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Safety / Usage

- Always use sudo for hardware access (GPIO, IÂ²C, SPI).
- BBG pins use 3.3V logic, except the 5V/VCC pins â†’ donâ€™t connect higher voltages directly.
- When using relays/motors â†’ use external power supplies and isolation.
- For AC mains â†’ only use properly rated relay modules.

ğŸ¦´ BeagleBone Green â€“ Example Codes

1.Blink Relay (GPIO)

import gpiod, time

chip = gpiod.Chip("gpiochip0")
line = chip.get_line(28)  # GPIO48 â†’ P9_15
line.request(consumer="relay", type=gpiod.LINE_REQ_DIR_OUT)

try:
    while True:
        line.set_value(1)  # Relay ON
        time.sleep(1)
        line.set_value(0)  # Relay OFF
        time.sleep(1)
except KeyboardInterrupt:
    line.set_value(0)
    line.release()
    chip.close()

2.IÂ²C Sensor Example (e.g., temperature sensor)

import smbus, time

bus = smbus.SMBus(2)   # IÂ²C bus 2 on BBG
address = 0x48         # Example sensor address

while True:
    temp = bus.read_byte(address)
    print(f"Temperature: {temp}Â°C")
    time.sleep(1)

